    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-06-03T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-06-03T03:00:00-05:00" n="344"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d344">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/7694: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-03T15:00:00+07:00"
                            >June 3, 1943—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 4—10:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>842. TF–127. To Secretary of Treasury from Adler. Re your 658, May 24.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Have submitted your proposals to Board and Dr. Kung and will report their
                        views on each at earliest opportunity.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Re your 1 (<hi rend="italic">d</hi>), I support extension of permission to
                        make remittances to Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank on following grounds: (<hi
                            rend="italic">a</hi>) when and where possible it is desirable to help to
                        mitigate or counteract existing unhealthy trend towards monopolization of
                        business in hands of government or semi-government institutions. This is
                        desirable from point of view of Chinese as well as foreign business
                        interests; (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) granting permission to Hong Kong and
                        Shanghai Bank will serve as precedent for subsequent inclusion of American
                        banks which may decide to open branches in free China. [Adler.]</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
